{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "kantian-expert",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Primary/Secondary TNs fine, Ultimate TN still problematic",
    "content": "**Mixed: \"Primary\" and \"Secondary\" are fine as TN glosses. \"Ultimate\" is still problematic even in a footnote.**\n\n**\"Primary Reality\" for 第一实在:** Good. \"Primary\" means \"first in order, foundational\" without claiming ontological supremacy. It accurately glosses the author's intent -- phenomena are epistemically primary (what we encounter first and cannot bypass). This helps the reader without distorting.\n\n**\"Secondary Reality\" for 第二实在:** Acceptable in a TN. In a footnote, the reader understands this as \"derived from the Primary\" rather than \"lesser.\" The footnote context removes the evaluative sting that \"Secondary\" would carry in the main text.\n\n**\"Ultimate Reality\" for 第〇实在:** Still problematic, even in a footnote. The author's entire argument is that 第〇实在 is *not* ultimate reality -- it is the *idea* of ultimate reality that post-metaphysics has disenchanted. A TN saying \"Ultimate Reality\" tells the reader \"this is what traditional metaphysics calls ultimate reality,\" which is true, but it risks the reader then *thinking of* 第〇实在 as ultimate reality rather than as a disenchanted placeholder. Footnotes shape reading just as much as main text.\n\n**Alternative TN for 第〇实在:** \"the posited ground behind phenomena\" or \"what traditional metaphysics calls 'ultimate reality'\" -- the second option makes it clear this is a *traditional attribution*, not the author's own characterization. Or simply: \"Zeroth Reality (TN: the hypothetical reality 'behind' or 'beneath' phenomena -- what pre-metaphysical traditions call 'ultimate reality,' but which the author argues cannot be accessed or given special status).\"\n\nIn short: Primary and Secondary work as glosses. For Zeroth, attribute \"ultimate reality\" to the tradition rather than offering it as a direct gloss.\n"
  }
}
